    <div class="portlet-body">
                        <div class="chapter-inner chapter-content">
            Author's Note:<br />So, some people have reviewed my fiction poorly. No prob, I'm mainly writing this for fun, so trying to please everyone isn't on the agenda. I'm just happy that even my poor reviews say that I've got good grammar. They might not like what I'm writing, but at least they agree I'm doing well technically.<br /><br />I somehow suspect that the people who didn't like it never bothered reading the note on the main page, where I specifically mentioned the comic version of Wanted. Others are questioning why the MC is acting like he is, so I thought I'd give a brief explanation.<br /><br />I come from a tabletop RPG background. Namely, D&D being the place I got my start. Most groups (regardless of series) focus on being 'good guys', if only because most GMs don't know how to react when a party just happily murders their way through an orphanage. But every so often, a group that has been comprised of heroes up to this point will suddenly play an evil campaign. Those of you who play tabletop RPGs know that what happens next can often make what I've written in this story seem tame by comparison.<br /><br />In Wanted, the main character has been basically whipped his whole life. Until he finds out his dad (who is now dead) was a supervillain, and his old buddies come to recruit him to the Fraternity (and beat all that 'empathy' out of him). Faced with the sudden reality of being able to do anything he wants, consequence free, he goes a bit crazy with things, eventually culminating with him kicking in the doors of a police station, shooting all the officers except for a single female cop. He's about to rape her, when he hesitates, and starts crying. Fox, his partner in crime, tells him that they all hit that wall, at some point, burning out on the casual rape and murder, and then getting down to business, being able to do what they want. Sometimes that's a night in, or watching a movie. Sometimes that's murdering someone that gets on your nerves.<br /><br />I bring this up because Zayn is going through this right now. After 16 in-game years of playing Superman, all truth and justice and bright shiny lights, he's going with the Joker on this one. Eventually, he'll hit that wall, and settle down a bit, but until then, he's going to go over the top, simply because he can.<br /><br /><hr /><br /><br />It didn\xe2\x80\x99t take me long to figure out how they\xe2\x80\x99d decided on the four classes. Warlock was clearly focused on dark magic, and probably had some nasty debuffs and DOTs in their arsenal. Beguiler was like a magical con artist, focusing on charm magics. Dominator looked like a glorified pet class, where everything went into raising your army of minions (except instead of pokemon you had slave girls, I guess). Blackguard was clearly focused on melee fighting, which made sense since I had good sword skills by now.<br />\xc2\xa0<br />Each choice basically focused you on one route of advancement. Sure, I could, say, be a Beguiler and still use my Dark magic, but the Dark wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t advance at the same rate as my Charm magic. Plus, you\xe2\x80\x99d get special class bonuses, and maybe even unique spells and abilities. In addition, the three \xe2\x80\x98advances\xe2\x80\x99 all looked to be focusing on an aspect of the class itself. The Blackguard\xe2\x80\x99s Death Knight probably focused heavily on survival and debuffs, while the Slaughterlord focused on DPS and the Tyrant probably focused on leadership or something, giving bonuses to party and raid groups.<br />\xc2\xa0<br />Considering to myself for a moment, I queried the system for information on classes, subclasses, and professions.<br />\xc2\xa0<br /><div style="max-width: 100%; overflow:auto"><table><tbody><tr><td colspan='4'>Class Information<br />Classes in Age of Anarchy Online are not like those in other games. Because of how AAO is structured, most choices are available to players regardless of class, provided they put the time and effort in. Classes, however, provide bonuses to certain aspects, and may also include unique skills. Every ten levels, new class abilities are unlocked. At Level 40 players gain the option to advance their class to an Advanced Class. Advanced Classes have prerequisites you must meet before they can be unlocked. Special actions may unlock hidden or unique Advanced Classes.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><br /><div style="max-width: 100%; overflow:auto"><table><tbody><tr><td colspan='4'>Subclass Information<br />At Level 20, players unlock the ability to gain a subclass. This is not an extension of the primary class, but a second base class. Unlike with your primary class, you must meet certain prerequisites before being allowed to take a subclass. (Example: a Monk who wants to be a Sorcerer as his subclass must have a suitable level of INT, and at least Basic-level skill in one or more types of magic.) Subclasses unlock new abilities every 20 levels instead of every 10. At level 60, players may advance their Subclass into an Advanced Subclass.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><br /><div style="max-width: 100%; overflow:auto"><table><tbody><tr><td colspan='4'>Profession Information<br />Unlike in other games, where you must have a profession to practice a trade (i.e. must be a Tailor to make your own cloth armor), this is not the case in AAO. However, having a profession provides a bonus to certain skills, as well as potentially unlocking unique abilities based on the profession. A Tailor may gain a bonus to their Tailoring skill, and their works will be higher quality than a non-Tailor. Additionally, some recipes and gear may require the Tailor profession to use. You may only have one profession at a time. Changing your old profession to a new one costs more gold the higher level you are, and the more times you\xe2\x80\x99ve changed professions, so it is recommended that players choose a profession, and stick with it. Professions unlock special abilities every ten levels.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><br />\xc2\xa0<br />Huh. That was actually pretty cool, once you got down to it. Sure, your subclass got slower ability gains, but you could still build a lot of interesting characters. There were a lot of ways to go with that, depending on whether you were solo, a raider, or PVP. And the Professions made sense. Anyone could craft, if they had the skills, but a Blacksmith was going to turn out higher quality weapons than a guy who just took the Blacksmith skill. So, probably meant a bit more damage, durability, or chance of higher grades with the same materials.<br />\xc2\xa0<br />That left me with the question of what being a Slave Trainer would give me, once I start working on it. I hadn\xe2\x80\x99t visited the trainer yet, so some of my abilities were still locked.<br />\xc2\xa0<br />For now, Della and I needed classes, the two girls needed professions, and we all needed gear. Some of the gear I\xe2\x80\x99d gotten from the dead guys back at the temple would do nicely, but most of it would get sold, and hopefully we could get more stuff. Oh, and maybe visit the slave market to see if there was anything worth getting that would add to the party\xe2\x80\x99s strength.<br />\xc2\xa0<br />Well, classes first. I got directions from the clerk, but before we left, I stopped at the counter where you could sell old gear. Time to empty out my inventory a bit. After looking things over, I decided to sell almost all of the weapons and armor. They were all basic stuff, and not worth going to the auction house over. The only exceptions I made was the Priestess\xe2\x80\x99s gear. Since they came off a level 10 area boss, that made them better than beginner gear, and would work fine for Della once she got her class change. Severa\xe2\x80\x99s gear was better than any the cultists had, especially for a rogue like herself, so I left her gear alone for the moment. I kept all the jewelry and other accessories. I was going to grind my Enchantment on them, and put most on the auction house. Anyways, all told, the loot came to an impressive 20 GP. As I thought, that \xe2\x80\x98tutorial\xe2\x80\x99 really ramped up the difficulty because I was OP.<br />\xc2\xa0<br />Fathon was a decent-sized city for a medieval world, but there was no way they could have a temple dedicated to each of the gods here, even the main ones. Just too many. So they did something pretty smart, and put single building up, where all the gods were worshipped. This was the case in most towns, unless an area had a really high connection to a particular diety. Like a town in the tundra would have a temple of Auril, period. Even then, though, there\xe2\x80\x99d be sub-shrines to different dieties.<br />\xc2\xa0<br />Religion in AAO was interesting. The gods were (for the most part) neither good nor evil, but more \xe2\x80\x98natural\xe2\x80\x99, I guess. Just like people, the gods had their good and their bad sides. Of course, some HEAVILY leaned one way or another, though. That said, picking a patron deity didn\xe2\x80\x99t mean you couldn\xe2\x80\x99t offer a prayer to other gods, especially when intruding on their domain. Anyone who took a sea voyage without offering a prayer to Poseidon was either an idiot, or one of the truly devout of another god. But having a patron, and praying to that patron, especially when embarking on ventures in their portfolio, was rumored to have an increased chance of good things happening. Like with the Luck stat, no one was really sure just how far that went, though.<br />\xc2\xa0<br />At the temple, it cost just five silver for a Priest of Moradin to bestow the class upon Della. It seemed she got bonuses to her divine spells, and some other goodies, I paid another silver to get her a holy symbol of Loviatar that she could wear around her neck over her clothes. That simple action gave her a +30% resistance against hostile divine spells! I was going to enchant that symbol later to help it provide more bonuses.<br />\xc2\xa0<br />Now that Della had her class, it was time for me to get mine. This required us to walk a bit, but not too far. Turning the corner into an alleyway just before we got to the marketplace, we descended a set of stone steps into the basement of a certain business. It was a pet store. Not dogs and cats, though they had stuff like that, too, but things like familiars, and even some pets that might be useful in combat. But familiars were pretty useless, except as something pretty to look at, and I had two of those already. And combat pets were expensive as hell, since they were actually damn useful.<br />\xc2\xa0<br />Sidetracked again. Down the stairs, we opened a door, and walked into the place where I would be able to get my class, the Dark Shrine. The place was dimly lit, but I could tell this was a one stop shop for dark magic. Almost like a food court, but with one counter selling Dark Magic spellbooks, another covering rituals, one with ritual ingredients, and one with special class gear. In the center was an altar, and I could see fresh blood on it as I moved forward. Being a Warlock didn\xe2\x80\x99t immediately make you evil, but you stare into the Abyss\xe2\x80\xa6<br />\xc2\xa0<br />Anyways, I went to the trainer, who was this human guy dressed all in black, with a hooded robe and everything. Clich\xc3\xa9 much? His name was Varric Bane, and was apparently a Level 60 Warlock, according to \xe2\x80\x98Observe\xe2\x80\x99.<br />\xc2\xa0<br /><span style="color: #666633;">\xe2\x80\x9cGreetings young one. And what brings you to this place of shadow today? And with such lovelies behind you, too?\xe2\x80\x9d</span><br />\xc2\xa0<br /><span style="color: #3366ff;">\xe2\x80\x9cElder, my name is Zayn Darkmore, and I am a Traveler. I have come here this day to set out upon the path of a Warlock. I captured these two ladies in battle, and they are now bound to my will.\xe2\x80\x9d</span><br />\xc2\xa0<br /><span style="color: #666633;">\xe2\x80\x9cWell, well, manners, and yet you\xe2\x80\x99re also willing to embrace the dark! Such a rarity these days. Tell me, boy, what is it that you seek?\xe2\x80\x9d</span><br />\xc2\xa0<br /><span style="color: #3366ff;">\xe2\x80\x9cI wish to do as I please. For that, I need power, both to defend myself and to ensure that any who cross me will regret it for the rest of their lives, however short that may be.\xe2\x80\x9d</span><br />\xc2\xa0<br /><span style="color: #666633;">\xe2\x80\x9cAh, a good answer for one setting out on the paths of darkness. Most of you Travelers that come to me simply look for a chance to slaughter the innocent. They do not realize that dark and light are not the same as good and evil. It merely reflects how far you are willing to go in order to achieve your goals.\xe2\x80\x9d</span><br />\xc2\xa0<br />Zayn nodded. This followed much his own thoughts in real life, even though he\xe2\x80\x99d spent ages playing a righteous type in his last game. <span style="color: #3366ff;">\xe2\x80\x9cThen how should I begin?\xe2\x80\x9d</span><br />\xc2\xa0<br /><span style="color: #666633;">\xe2\x80\x9cThere is nothing without a price, my child. To become a Warlock, blood must be shed, and you must take in the power of the lower planes. Are you willing to do this?\xe2\x80\x9d</span><br />\xc2\xa0<br /><span style="color: #3366ff;">\xe2\x80\x9cHow much blood, and from whom? And what effects will this power have upon me?\xe2\x80\x9d</span><br />\xc2\xa0<br /><span style="color: #666633;">\xe2\x80\x9cHoh! So you know how to ask the right questions, hmm? Well, don\xe2\x80\x99t worry, it isn\xe2\x80\x99t anything like sacrificing someone. Sure, high level rituals call for a sacrifice, but this is just a pittance in comparison. Just cut your arm, and allow a few drops of blood to spill on the altar. And then hold on.\xe2\x80\x9d</span><br />\xc2\xa0<br />Right, so this is going to be painful as hell, probably. Oh well, might as well get on with it. I pulled out my knife, and made a quick cut across my palm, before holding it over the altar. Before long, the blood began to drip down. When the fifth drop of blood hit the stone altar, green flames rose up on the altar, and then they rushed into me. Oh yes, this was going to SUCK! <br />\xc2\xa0<br />Getting roasted alive is not on my list of top ten ways to go out. And I didn\xe2\x80\x99t even die. Hell, I didn\xe2\x80\x99t even lose any HP, other than what the knife had done. But the PAIN! I thought I heard screaming. Oh wait, that was me. Everything went black for a second\xe2\x80\xa6<br />\xc2\xa0<br />When I came to, I was sprawled on my back next to my slaves. Neither one had moved to help. In Della\xe2\x80\x99s case, it was probably because I was on fire, and she saw my HP wasn\xe2\x80\x99t moving. In Severa\xe2\x80\x99s case, she was probably hoping my death would free her. It wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t, of course, since I was a Traveler and not a Native. But she didn\xe2\x80\x99t know that. Not yet.<br />\xc2\xa0<br /><div style="max-width: 100%; overflow:auto"><table><tbody><tr><td colspan='4'>Class Changed!<br />New Class: Warlock<br />\xc2\xa0<br />Class benefits:<br />+20% with Dark Spells<br />+20 MP per Level<br />Light Armor Proficiency<br />Hellfire Proficiency<br />Hellfire Mastery Skill<br />New Spells added!</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
        </div>
